# Hybrid vsim: QEMU + Verilator Co-simulation

## TL;DR

`vsim` runs RTL at ~5-9 KHz. A typical workload spends 99% of cycles in
boot, libc init, and warm-up before reaching the kernel under study.
Hybrid mode runs that boring prefix in QEMU at MHz speeds, hands the
architectural state to vsim for a small cycle-accurate Region of
Interest (ROI), then optionally hands back to QEMU to finish. The ROI
boundaries are marked in the guest binary by writing to a magic CSR
(`0x7C0`).

This document is a starting point for new engineers joining the hybrid
work. It explains what state is exchanged between simulators, how
control flow crosses the boundary, what is verified end-to-end today,
and what is intentionally out of scope.

---

## 1. End-to-end picture

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    G[Guest ELF<br/>contains csrwi 0x7C0, 0/1]
    Q1[QEMU 1<br/>functional, fast]
    V[vsim<br/>RTL, cycle-accurate]
    Q2[QEMU 2<br/>functional, fast]

    G --> Q1
    Q1 -->|state.bin: x1..x31, PC| V
    V -->|state.bin: x1..x31, PC| Q2

    M[/"/dev/shm/vsim-ram (mmap)"/]
    Q1 <-->|MAP_SHARED| M
    V  <-->|MAP_SHARED| M
    Q2 <-->|MAP_SHARED| M
```

A single guest ELF runs through three processes in sequence. Memory is
backed by one host file that all three processes mmap. Registers are
copied through small `state.bin` snapshots between processes, because
each simulator owns its own register state internally.

