## 2. Architectural state exchange

There are two kinds of architectural state and they use very different
mechanisms.

### 2.1 Registers and PC: copy via `state.bin`

The cross-simulator register snapshot is a packed C struct defined in
`hybrid/include/state_abi.h`:

```c
struct hybrid_state_v1 {
    uint32_t magic;     // 'AHYB'
    uint32_t version;
    uint64_t flags;
    uint64_t pc;
    uint8_t  priv;      // hardcoded to 3 (M-mode) today
    uint64_t gpr[32];   // x0..x31; x0 is always 0
    /* future: f[32], csr[N], v[32 * VLEN/8] */
} __attribute__((packed));
```

Only `gpr[1..31]` and `pc` are actually round-tripped today. Everything
else in the table below is in the "Known limitations" list.

#### QEMU -> vsim (resume)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Plugin as hybrid_handoff.so<br/>(QEMU TCG plugin)
    participant File as state.bin
    participant Vsim as vsim main loop
    participant DM as RISC-V Debug Module<br/>(in RTL)

    Note over Plugin: csrwi 0x7C0, 0 retires
    Plugin->>Plugin: read x1..x31, pc via<br/>qemu_plugin_read_register
    Plugin->>File: write hybrid_state_v1
    Plugin->>Plugin: qemu_plugin_request_exit

    Vsim->>File: load_state(path)
    File-->>Vsim: validate magic + version
    Note over Vsim: hold reset, then halt via DM
    Vsim->>DM: Abstract Command write x1..x31
    Vsim->>DM: write DPC = pc
    Vsim->>DM: dret -> resume at pc
```

The vsim side uses the existing JTAG DMI infrastructure
(`src/platform/jtag_dtm.hpp`) in-process - no socket, no DPI. Each
register write is a Debug Module Abstract Command driven over the DMI
bus from `src/hybrid/resume_driver.hpp`. The full ~33 transactions take
hundreds of RTL cycles, negligible against the millions of cycles
saved.

Files: `src/hybrid/state_loader.hpp`,
`src/hybrid/resume_from_qemu.hpp`, `src/hybrid/resume_driver.hpp`,
`src/hybrid/abstract_command.hpp`.

#### vsim -> QEMU (handback)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Vsim as vsim main loop
    participant DM as RISC-V Debug Module
    participant File as state.bin
    participant Q2 as QEMU 2 (-gdb -S)
    participant GDB as gdbstub::Session

    Note over Vsim: csrwi 0x7C0, 1 retires
    Vsim->>DM: halt, read x1..x31, pc<br/>via Abstract Commands
    Vsim->>File: write hybrid_state_v1
    Vsim->>Vsim: run() returns kExitHandoffToQemu (200)
    Vsim->>Q2: fork+exec qemu-system-riscv64<br/>-gdb tcp::PORT -S
    Vsim->>GDB: connect_loopback (5 s budget)
    GDB->>Q2: P&lt;reg&gt;=&lt;value&gt; for x1..x31
    GDB->>Q2: P32=&lt;pc&gt;
    GDB->>Q2: c (continue)
    Q2->>Q2: run until semihosting exit
    Q2-->>Vsim: waitpid -> exit code
    Vsim-->>Vsim: propagate exit code
```

The handback uses QEMU's built-in gdbstub (`-gdb tcp::PORT -S` makes
QEMU pause at start and listen on a TCP port for GDB Remote Serial
Protocol packets). vsim implements just the subset needed to write
registers (`P<reg>=<value>`) and continue (`c`) in
`src/hybrid/gdbstub_client.hpp` and `src/hybrid/gdbstub_session.hpp`.

Files: `src/hybrid/state_drain.hpp`, `src/hybrid/qemu_handback.hpp`,
`src/hybrid/gdbstub_session.hpp`, `src/hybrid/gdbstub_client.hpp`.

### 2.2 Memory: share via mmap

Copying a register file is fine; copying gigabytes of guest RAM between
simulators is not. So we don't copy. We share.

```
host file: /dev/shm/vsim-ram (e.g. 128 MB, truncate-allocated)
                |
                +--- mmap MAP_SHARED ---> QEMU 1 RAM at GPA 0x80000000
                +--- mmap MAP_SHARED ---> vsim  RAM at GPA 0x80000000
                +--- mmap MAP_SHARED ---> QEMU 2 RAM at GPA 0x80000000

GPA 0x80010000 -> file offset 0x10000  (in all three processes)
```

QEMU sees this through `-object memory-backend-file,id=mem,share=on,mem-path=...
,size=...` plus `-machine virt,memory-backend=mem`. The `virt` machine
puts RAM at GPA `0x80000000` (the base is hardcoded in QEMU's
`hw/riscv/virt.c`).

vsim sees the same file through `--shared-mem-path PATH
--shared-mem-size N`. Internally:

- `MmapBacking` (`src/platform/mmap_backing.hpp`) opens the file and
  hands a `std::span<uint8_t>` to `SimpleMemory`.
- `SimpleMemory`'s `MemoryRegion` is narrowed to `[base, base+size)`
  with `base = 0x80000000` (the `--shared-mem-base` flag, defaulting to
  the QEMU virt RAM base). With the narrow region, the SimpleMemory
  translation `addr - region.base_address` makes file byte 0 correspond
  to GPA `0x80000000`, exactly as in QEMU.
- `Simulator::load_elf` uses `region.base_address` as the load base,
  so an ELF segment at GPA `0x80000000` lands at file offset `0`.

When `--shared-mem-path` is unset, vsim falls back to a `std::vector`
big enough for the wide `[RAM_BASE=0, RAM_END=0x8FFFFFFF]` region. All
existing non-hybrid tests use this path unchanged.

A 4 KB write in vsim at GPA `0x80010000` is observable by an
independent host process that mmaps the same file at offset `0x10000`.
This is the property `tests/hybrid/shared_mem_offset.test.cpp` and
`tests/hybrid/rt_shared_mem.sh` lock in.

Files: `src/platform/mmap_backing.hpp`, `src/platform/simple_memory.hpp`,
`src/platform/platform.hpp`, `src/main.cpp` (CLI flags).

