## 3. Control flow exchange

### 3.1 The `0x7C0` magic CSR

`0x7C0` is a user-defined RISC-V CSR address with no architectural
meaning. The hybrid system claims it as the boundary marker:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[guest ELF retires<br/>csrwi 0x7C0, imm] --> B{imm}
    B -->|0| C[ENTER detail<br/>QEMU drains, exits]
    B -->|1| D[EXIT detail<br/>vsim drains, returns 200]

    E[guest ELF retires<br/>csrrw rd, 0x7C0, rs1] --> F{value of GPR rs1}
    F -->|0| C
    F -->|1| D
```

Two equivalent encodings are accepted:

- **Immediate form** (`csrwi 0x7C0, 0` / `csrwi 0x7C0, 1`): the simplest
  fixture style.
- **Runtime form** (`csrrw rd, 0x7C0, rs1`): the fixture loads `0` or
  `1` into a GPR first; the trigger reads that GPR's live value.
  Useful when the boundary is computed at runtime.

QEMU sees the trigger via a TCG plugin
(`hybrid/qemu_plugin/hybrid_handoff.c`) registered with
`qemu_plugin_register_vcpu_insn_exec_cb()`. The plugin pre-decodes
each instruction once; the per-instruction callback only fires on a
matching `csrrw`/`csrwi` opcode.

vsim sees the trigger via the existing retire signal taps. Before the
ROI starts, `Simulator::enable_hybrid_handoff()` (defined in
`src/simulator.hpp`) pre-scans the ELF for PCs whose instruction is a
write to `0x7C0`. During the run loop, a retire of one of those PCs
calls the `HandoffController` (`src/hybrid/handoff_controller.hpp`)
which decodes the immediate / GPR value and either drains state or
ignores the event.

We deliberately avoid HTIF (`tohost`/`fromhost`) and `ecall`, which
already have meanings.

### 3.2 The `--resume-from-qemu` / `--qemu-binary` plumbing

The vsim CLI exposes three flags that together drive a round-trip:

| Flag | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `--resume-from-qemu PATH` | Load `PATH` as the entry-state snapshot. After `reset()`, drive the DM to write registers + PC. |
| `--handoff-out PATH` | After this point the run loop watches retires for `csrwi/csrrw 0x7C0, *`. On exit-detail (value 1), drain state to `PATH` and exit with code 200. |
| `--qemu-binary PATH` | When the run exits with code 200, fork+exec `PATH` with `-gdb tcp::PORT -S`, restore state via gdbstub, propagate QEMU's exit code. |

Set just `--resume-from-qemu` for one-way QEMU -> vsim.
Add `--handoff-out` to drain state on the way out of vsim.
Add `--qemu-binary` to also do the vsim -> QEMU 2 handback.

The shared-memory flags layer onto the same flow:

| Flag | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `--shared-mem-path PATH` | mmap-backed file used as main RAM. Required for cross-simulator memory survival. |
| `--shared-mem-size N` | Size of the mmap region (must match QEMU's `size=` argument). |
| `--shared-mem-base HEX` | GPA that file offset 0 maps to. Default `0x80000000`. Override only for non-`virt` machine types. |

`run_qemu_handback` propagates these to QEMU 2's command line so all
three processes see the same backing file.

