## 4. Verified end-to-end test cases

All twelve drivers live under `tests/hybrid/` and are wired into CTest
under the `hybrid-e2e` label. They `exit 77` (skip) when the QEMU
binary, plugin, or fixture ELFs are missing, so a clean container gives
SKIP not FAIL.

Run the full suite with:

```bash
ctest -L hybrid-e2e --output-on-failure   # from build/
```

### 4.1 Tier-1: round-trip happy paths (8)

Each fixture follows the three-phase template (Phase A in QEMU 1,
Phase B in vsim, Phase C in QEMU 2). Pass/fail is the QEMU 2
process exit code, propagated by vsim.

| Driver | Fixture | What it verifies | Pass code |
|---|---|---|---|
| `test_e2e_handoff_roundtrip` | `handoff_roundtrip.S` | Baseline: minimal `a2 = 1 + 2 = 3` round-trip, PC and one GPR survive both handoffs. | 3 |
| `test_e2e_rt_pc_jump` | `rt_pc_jump.S` | PC fidelity: Phase B `j .+0x40` puts the exit csrwi 64 bytes ahead of where it started. | 0 |
| `test_e2e_rt_sign_bits` | `rt_sign_bits.S` | 64-bit width fidelity through the DM Abstract Command path: `0`, `-1`, `0x8000_..._0`, `0x7FFF_..._F`, `0x0000_..._F`. | 0 |
| `test_e2e_rt_abi_aliases` | `rt_abi_aliases.S` | `ra (x1)`, `sp (x2)`, `gp (x3)`, `tp (x4)`, `fp (x8)` all survive untouched across two handoffs. | 0 |
| `test_e2e_rt_long_roi` | `rt_long_roi.S` | Vsim runs a 100-iteration loop summing 1..100 = 5050; catches resume-state corruption only visible after many cycles. | 0 |
| `test_e2e_rt_all_gprs` | `rt_all_gprs.S` | All 31 GPRs survive QEMU 1 -> vsim -> QEMU 2; bit `i` of `t2` reports a mismatch on register `i`. | 0 |
| `test_e2e_rt_mem_loadstore` | `rt_mem_loadstore.S` | Vsim's memory subsystem under load while resumed from foreign state: load-after-store, RAW within vsim's pipeline. | 0 |
| `test_e2e_rt_unaligned_lh` | `rt_unaligned_lh.S` | Halfword/byte loads at unaligned addresses inside the vsim ROI. | 0 |

### 4.2 Tier-2: cross-simulator memory survival (1)

| Driver | What it verifies | Pass code |
|---|---|---|
| `test_e2e_rt_shared_mem` | Memory written by one simulator is visible to the next through the shared mmap. Phase A fills 4 KB at GPA `0x80010000` with `0xA5`; Phase B (vsim) verifies + XORs with `0x5A` to leave `0xFF`; Phase C (QEMU 2) reads back through the same mmap and confirms. | 0 |

This is the only test that detects regressions in "memory written in
vsim is visible to QEMU 2", the key promise of hybrid mode beyond
register transfer. It uses a separate driver (`rt_shared_mem.sh`)
because it allocates `/dev/shm` and adds `--shared-mem-*` CLI flags.

### 4.3 Negative / robustness drivers (3)

These guard quietly-degrading failure paths the happy-path tests can't
see.

| Driver | Failure mode | Asserts |
|---|---|---|
| `test_e2e_rt_corrupt_state` | Vsim is given a 32-byte truncated `state.bin`. | Exit non-zero, non-200, non-timeout; stderr matches `short read\|bad magic\|cannot open`. |
| `test_e2e_rt_no_qemu_binary` | `--qemu-binary /nonexistent`. Drain still fires; exec in the spawned child fails. | Exit `127` (standard exec-failure code), elapsed under 15 s. Surfaced via `connect_loopback` polling `waitpid(WNOHANG)` in parallel with `::connect`. |
| `test_e2e_rt_gdbstub_timeout` | `--qemu-binary` is `qemu_silent_stub.py`, which opens the gdb port, accepts the connection, and sleeps. | Vsim's `gdbstub::Session::recv_byte` hits `SO_RCVTIMEO=5 s`, throws "recv timeout", vsim exits non-zero in under 25 s. |

Together: vsim exits non-zero, exits cleanly, and exits promptly, in
each respective failure mode.

